<div id="review_72185799" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/72185799" />
    <a title="El" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/83144-el"><img alt="El" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1479156984p2/83144.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/72185799?book_show_action=true">Sep 22, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="El" class="user" itemprop="url" name="El" href="/user/show/83144-el">El</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780517585160" href="/book/show/761683.The_Information">review of another edition</a>


          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to El by: </span>
      Clovis brought it home.
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/83144-el?shelf=20th-centurylit-late">20th-centurylit-late</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer72185799" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1178880386842088148">Writers, apparently, are a curmudgeonly and vindictive lot. Richard Tull is the protagonist of Amis&apos;s 1995 novel, a once-promising hot new writer. But the real success story lies in his former roommate, Gwyn Barry, who has written a phenomenal novel. Tull, reduced to writing book reviews, is obsessed with his previous friend&apos;s success and can hardly understand it. This obsession leads Tull to try and bring Gwyn down, going about it in quite some impressive ways.<br/><br/>Amis is one of those writers I lov</span>
  <span id="freeText1178880386842088148" style="display:none">Writers, apparently, are a curmudgeonly and vindictive lot. Richard Tull is the protagonist of Amis's 1995 novel, a once-promising hot new writer. But the real success story lies in his former roommate, Gwyn Barry, who has written a phenomenal novel. Tull, reduced to writing book reviews, is obsessed with his previous friend's success and can hardly understand it. This obsession leads Tull to try and bring Gwyn down, going about it in quite some impressive ways.<br /><br />Amis is one of those writers I love and hate, for usually the same reasons. He has a way with language and prose that is fascinating to watch unfold on the page; at the same time it's annoying as hell - do I really need a sentence retold two lines later? It's repetitive. And redundant. But that's his writing style, isn't it, so I try to be fair about it.<br /><br />I wanted to say that this was Amis's novel about his experiences growing old - it felt to be a bitter story, like an old man. But then I realized he would have only been 46 at the time of the publication of this book, which is still relatively young. Tull focuses a lot of his energy on the idea of midlife crises, and how much of a crisis it would be to not have a midlife crisis at all.<br /><br />All in all, a good book, though not nearly as satisfying to me as <i>Time's Arrow</i>. But not dissatisfying enough to turn me off either.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1178880386842088148" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


