  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_151956581" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/151956581" />
    <a title="Drew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4675538-drew"><img alt="Drew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1299606167p2/4675538.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/151956581?book_show_action=true">Mar 03, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Drew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Drew" href="/user/show/4675538-drew">Drew</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer151956581" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17843787648367980601"><i>The Information</i> is a really good book that I can picture myself liking a lot better under different circumstances. Like, say, if it had been the first (Martin) Amis book I&apos;d read.<br/><br/>Amis does a good job describing a lot of the stuff that&apos;s arguably wrong with the sort of fiction that tends to become wildly successful these days. And, helpfully, he does an even better job of self-deprecatingly describing &quot;real&quot; &quot;literary&quot; fiction--the sort of fiction that strives to be difficult, the sort that Franz</span>
  <span id="freeText17843787648367980601" style="display:none"><i>The Information</i> is a really good book that I can picture myself liking a lot better under different circumstances. Like, say, if it had been the first (Martin) Amis book I'd read.<br /><br />Amis does a good job describing a lot of the stuff that's arguably wrong with the sort of fiction that tends to become wildly successful these days. And, helpfully, he does an even better job of self-deprecatingly describing "real" "literary" fiction--the sort of fiction that strives to be difficult, the sort that Franzen calls "status fiction." Gwyn Barry, the personification of the former, seems like not much more than a pandering simpleton who's lucked into everything he's got, but there's a cool little mean streak there too. Richard Tull, the personification of the latter, is barely more sympathetic; in fact, he's mostly just pathetic. Of particular hilarity are numerous accounts of various people having tried to read Tull's magnum opus, <i>Untitled</i>, and coming down with migraines or nystagmus or whatever. <br /><br />So that's the good. The bad is that in a lot of ways, it's just another Martin Amis book. A distinctive tone or voice is a great thing for an author, and it's a big part of what made me like <i>Money</i> so much when I read it a while back. But Amis's tone is pretty consistent throughout his work, as far as I can see, and if you get really used to it, there doesn't always seem to be that much more going on. <i>The Information</i> concerns itself with London's grotesques: petty criminals with names like Crash and Scozzy, down-and-out artists like Tull himself, the inevitable sad-sack character named Keith (a Keith appears in both <i>London Fields</i> and <i>Dead Babies</i>, and I can't remember, but I'm guessing there's probably one in <i>Money</i> too), etc. The characters are very distinctive physically--it seems like there are upwards of 30 pages devoted to describing Richard's body's quirks and foibles--but not always psychologically. Just one example: Richard has this very attractive wife, Gina, whom he seems to love. And who seems to love him. But since Richard, as a failed novelist and even a failed reviewer, is not bringing any money in, and is in addition kind of a dick, she's contemplating leaving him. And Richard's clearly afraid of this eventuality, but he does nothing to change the situation. Why not? And other similar questions.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17843787648367980601" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

